<a name="wacky"></a>

<hr size="1">
<font color="#666666" face="Verdana, Arial, Sans-serif" size="1">
WACKY WEB WEEK
<br><br></font>



<font face="Arial,Sans-serif" color="black" size="4"><b>

Don McMillan explains how not to use PowerPoint

</b><br></font>
<font face="Arial,Sans-Serif" color="black" size="1"><br></font>



<table width="100%" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" bgcolor="white" summary="Wacky Web Week">
<tr>
<td width="110" align="left" valign="top" bgcolor="FFFFFF">
<a href="http://WindowsSecrets.com/links/p3472n61w1axd/528c4ah/?url=www.youtube.com%2Fwatch%3Fv%3DHLpjrHzgSRM">
<img src="http://windowssecrets.com/images/wsn/W070621-PowerPoint-By-Don-M.jpg"
align="left" width="100" height="68" border="0" hspace="0" vspace="3"
title="Don McMillan" alt="Don McMillan"></a>
</td>

<td width="510" align="left" valign="top" bgcolor="FFFFFF">

<font face="Arial,Sans-serif" color="#000000" size="2">
We've all seen PowerPoint presentations run amok. The melange of fonts, the garish colors, the bullet lists that go on forever.<br><br>

These mishaps are not lost on comedian Don McMillan. In this short clip, he provides some quick pointers for keeping your PowerPoint presentation from becoming a multimedia nightmare.
<a href="http://WindowsSecrets.com/links/p3472n61w1axd/528c4ah/?url=www.youtube.com%2Fwatch%3Fv%3DHLpjrHzgSRM" name="ws_wacky web week">
Watch the video</a><br></font>

</td>
</tr>
</table>



